<!DOCTYPE article PUBLIC "-//OASIS//DTD DocBook V3.1//EN" [
]>

<article>
  <artheader>
    <title>
      Requirements for Hermes: The Home Exercise Program
    </title>
    <author>
      <firstname>Chuck</firstname>
      <surname>Hardin</surname>
    </author>
  </artheader>

  <sect1>
    <title>Abstract</title>
    <para>
      Hermes is an application which guides a user through exercise
      routines and logs her progress.  It uses audio cues during a
      routine as the primary means of pacing movements.  This document
      specifies the requirements for such a system.
    </para>      
  </sect1>

  <sect1>
    <title>Background</title>
    <para>
      I've
      used <ulink url='https://www.medbridgego.com/access_token'>MedBridge
      GO</ulink> to guide my home exercise program, to share my
      exercise progress with my physical therapist, and later to
      record that progress when my time with her was over.  It's not a
      bad app, but it has a number of shortcomings for my use, and I
      have not seen a replacement that will fill those lacunae.</para>
    <sect2>
      <title>Benefits of MedBridge GO</title>
      <itemizedlist>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    It presents a routine as a collection of exercises.  An
	    exercise has a count of sets, a count of reps per set, and
	    a sequence of moves per rep with specified timing.  This
	    is fairly easy to grasp in concept and suggests a
	    straightforward data representation.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    It provides the user with a simple visual and audio guide
	    to perform an exercise routine.  She is guided through
	    every motion.  Supplementary hints about how best to
	    perform each exercise are available by hitting an
	    information icon.  The user does not need to keep count of
	    reps or provide their own timing; the app does that for
	    her, leaving her free to concentrate on her form.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    It gives the user an easy way to save their progress after
	    completing a routine.  The typical use case requires only
	    a few button presses and the thing is done.</para>
	</listitem>
      </itemizedlist>
    </sect2>
    <sect2>
      <title>Drawbacks of MedBridge GO</title>
      <itemizedlist>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    It doesn't allow the user to alter her regimen
	    autonomously.  Only her therapist can do that.  As I have
	    progressed, I find I want to add sets to an exercise or
	    new exercises to a routine.  MedBridge GO does not support
	    that.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    It doesn't make allowance for noting changes in the
	    intensity of an exercise other than rep count or elapsed
	    time.  For example, there is no way to record changes in
	    resistance.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    Its cues are mostly visual, in the form of videos.  There
	    are few audio indications of progress, mostly a tone at
	    the beginning of the last three reps of an exercise.  This
	    requires me to look at a screen during exercises, which I
	    find inconvenient.  At the least, I want audio cues at
	    critical parts of an exercise and a cue for each
	    rep.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    It requires an internet connection to function and uses
	    that connection to send exercise information to its
	    servers. I may not want to share that with others.  I may
	    in future want to add that capability, but I do not want
	    it by default.  I prefer my privacy.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    It allows only a limited ability to keep track of changes
	    to the user's regimen over time.  A user can enter such
	    changes when recording a given exercise session, but I
	    cannot see them in the interface.  Also, as previously
	    stated, those user-recorded changes do not persist for
	    future routines, since only the therapist can make
	    permanent changes to a routine.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    MedBridge GO does not provide its source code.  I want to
	    be able to change the system's behavior, possibly in ways
	    I do not currently anticipate.  It is very likely that I
	    will share this code publicly under an open source
	    license, possibly the AGPL.</para>
	</listitem>
      </itemizedlist>
    </sect2>
  </sect1>

  <sect1>
    <title>Why Hermes?</title>
    <sect2>
      <title>Why the name?</title>
      <para>
	Hermes
	was <ulink url='https://www.theoi.com/Olympios/HermesGod.html'>the
	god of athletes</ulink>, among other things.</para>
    </sect2>
    <sect2>
      <title>Why bother?</title>
      <para>
        Aside from the unsuitability of the known alternatives?  I
        thought it'd be fun, and a good way to brush up on my
        Python.</para>
    </sect2>
  </sect1>
  
  <sect1>
    <title>Phased requirements</title>
    <sect2>
      <title>Storing routines and generating audio output</title>
      <sect3>
	<title>Storing routine data</title>
	<orderedlist>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      The app must support multiple users, each with their own
	      routine data.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      A user must have a globally unique username and can have
	      routines.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      A routine is specific to a user.  It must have a name
	      which is unique for that user and may have
	      exercises.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      An exercise may be attached to any number of routines.
	      It must have a name, a count of sets, a count of reps
	      per set, and a sequence of moves.
	      <orderedlist>
		<listitem>
		  <para>
		    The name may be used to generate an audio hint to
		    signal the commencement of a set.</para>
		</listitem>
		<listitem>
		  <para>
		    An exercise may have a supplemental description of
		    the desired form for that exercise.</para>
		</listitem>
		<listitem>
		  <para>
		    An exercise may have a link to a reference video
		    for that exercise.  Optimally this will be a
		    reliably persistent link, such as those provided
		    by <ulink url='https://preservetube.com/'>PreserveTube</ulink>.</para>
		</listitem>
		<listitem>
		  <para>
		    An exercise may have a set of key-value pairs to
		    describe properties of the exercise, such as its
		    intensity.</para>
		</listitem>
		<listitem>
		  <para>
		    An exercise may be specific to a user, or may be
		    generic as a template for other users to use as a
		    basis for their own exercises.  A user may not
		    edit a generic template, but may clone it for
		    their own use, or create their own.  A cloned
		    exercise may have its own set of associated
		    key-value pairs.</para>
		  <para>
		    The name of a generic exercise must be globally
		    unique among all generic exercises.  The name of a
		    user-specific exercise must be unique for that
		    user.</para>
		</listitem>
	      </orderedlist>
	    </para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      A move must have a specified duration and may have a
	      description.  This description may be used to generate
	      an audio hint to accompany the performance of that
	      move.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      All of the data above must be persistently storable and
	      retrievable.  A user should be able to search and
	      retrieve generic data and to search, retrieve, edit, and
	      create their specific data.</para>
	  </listitem>
	</orderedlist>
      </sect3>
      <sect3>
	<title>Generating audio output</title>
	<orderedlist>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      For this phase, it is sufficient to implement a utility
	      which can be invoked from a command line to create an
	      audio file which can be used to guide a user through a
	      routine.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      The audio output will be a rendition of the steps for
	      the given routine.  If possible, the utility should
	      provide a selection of voices, with a default voice
	      provided and others specified by an argument to the
	      command.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      The beginning of the audio output will state the name of
	      the routine and give the user a delay before starting.
	      This delay will have a default duration that can be
	      overridden by an argument to the command.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      For each exercise in the given routine, the audio output
	      will state the name of the exercise.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      For each set in the given exercise, the audio output
	      will prompt the user to begin.  This prompt will be an
	      audio rendition of a text string which will have a
	      default value that can be overridden by an argument to
	      the command.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      The audio output will repeat the audio for each set of
	      moves for the specified number of reps.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      For each move in the given rep, the audio output will
	      state the description of the move, if provided.  The
	      only exception is the prompt to begin at the start of
	      the exercise.  The audio output will then be padded or
	      truncated so that the duration of the audio output for
	      the given move equals its specified duration in the
	      data.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      At the end of each set, the audio output will prompt the
	      user to pause before beginning the next one.  This
	      prompt will be an audio rendition of a phrase which will
	      have a default value that can be overridden by an
	      argument to the command.  The duration of the pause will
	      have a default value that can be overridden by an
	      argument to the command.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      At the end of the routine, the audio output will prompt
	      the user that the routine is finished.  This prompt will
	      be an audio rendition of a phrase which will have a
	      default value that can be overridden by an argument to
	      the command.</para>
	  </listitem>
	</orderedlist>
      </sect3>
      <sect3>
	<title>Deliverable for this phase</title>
	<para>
	  When this phase is complete, a user will be able to enter
	  data for any of their exercise routines and generate audio
	  output to guide the user through performing those
	  routines.</para>
      </sect3>
    </sect2>
    <sect2>
      <title>Storing progress and serving generated audio via the Internet</title>
      <orderedlist>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    There will be an access-controlled web interface to
	    perform various functions for a user to access their
	    routine data.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    This web interface will let the user store their exercise
	    progress over time.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    It will also give the user access to generated audio to
	    guide their performance of a given routine.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    The above functions will be smoothly integrated into a
	    single flow.</para>
	</listitem>
      </orderedlist>
      <sect3>
	<title>Storing progress via a web interface</title>
	<orderedlist>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      A user can record the fact that they have completed a
	      given routine at a given date and time, which by default
	      will be the date and time at which they recorded that
	      fact.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      The user may record their progress in this way:</para>
	    <orderedlist>
	      <listitem>
		<para>
		  Once the user is authenticated, they may choose a
		  routine for which they want to record progress.  This
		  selection will be from a list of names of routines for
		  that user.</para>
	      </listitem>
	      <listitem>
		<para>
		  The stored progress for a routine will include a
		  static snapshot of the exercises in the routine at
		  the time it was performed.  This will include data
		  on the moves and the properties of the
		  exercise</para>
	      </listitem>
	      <listitem>
		<para>
		  The user may add notes on their performance which are
		  attached to that record.  These notes will be freeform
		  text which will be entered as plain text.</para>
	      </listitem>
	      <listitem>
		<para>
		  Progress records are stored persistently.</para>
	      </listitem>
	    </orderedlist>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      The user may also view their past records.  A record
	      will have a link to view the data for the static
	      snapshot of the roputine, and will render performance
	      notes as
	      <ulink url='https://www.markdownguide.org/'>Markdown</ulink>.</para>
	  </listitem>
	</orderedlist>
      </sect3>
      <sect3>
	<title>Serving generated audio via a web interface</title>
	<orderedlist>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      A user may use the same access-controlled web interface
	      to serve the generated audio described in the previous
	      phase.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      The audio will be current with respect to the routine
	      data at the time it is served.</para>
	  </listitem>
	</orderedlist>
      </sect3>
      <sect3>
	<title>Deliverable for this phase</title>
	<para>
	  When this phase is complete, a user will get generated audio
	  for a given exercise routine and then record their progress
	  for that routine.</para>
      </sect3>
    </sect2>
    <sect2>
      <title>TODO: Editing routines via a web interface</title>
      <warning>
	<para>This section is not fleshed out.</para>
      </warning>
      <sect3>
	<title>Requirements of the server</title>
	<orderedlist>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      The server must be able to communicate with the
	      persistence mechanism used to store, change, and
	      retrieve routine data.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      The server must supply a RESTful interface through an
	      HTTPS connection to perform these operations on the
	      persistence layer.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      Access to the RESTful API must be access-controlled per
	      user.  This access will be scoped to the user.  A user
	      can only perform operations on their data and can only
	      view generic data.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      The server will supply an access-controlled web
	      interface to perform these operations on a user's
	      routine data.</para>
	  </listitem>
	</orderedlist>
      </sect3>
      <sect3>
	<title>Requirements of the client</title>
	<orderedlist>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      The client can use a browser to communicate with the
	      server's web interface.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      At some point, the client may have an Android app to
	      supply the capabilities of the web interface.</para>
	  </listitem>
	</orderedlist>
      </sect3>
    </sect2>
  </sect1>
  
 </article>
